{"ts": "2026-06-07T21:24:46.402465+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Here’s the full walkthrough of the database migrations in this repository, based on the authoritative `MIGRATION_HISTORY.md` and the actual SQL files currently checked in.\n\n---\n\n## Migration ordering\n\nThey are applied strictly in numeric prefix order (001 → 002 → … → 006).  \nThe current `migrations/` folder only contains files **001–003**; files **004–006** have been archived (as noted in `MIGRATION_HISTORY.md`) but are listed there as having been run in deployed environments.\n\n---\n\n## 1. `001_create_users.sql` (2024-11-04)\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE users (\n    id           BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n    email        TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n    display_name TEXT,\n    created_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()\n);\n```\n\n**What it does:**  \nCreates the foundational `users` table. Each user gets an auto‑incrementing `id`, a unique `email` (required), an optional `display_name`, and a timestamp `created_at` that defaults to the current time.\n\n---\n\n## 2. `002_create_sessions.sql` (2024-12-10)\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE sessions (\n    id          UUID PRIMARY KEY,\n    user_id     BIGINT NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n    issued_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),\n    expires_at  TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL\n);\n```\n\n**What it does:**  \nCreates the `sessions` table for user authentication/authorization. Each session has a UUID primary key, a foreign key to `users(id)` (with `ON DELETE CASCADE` — if the user is removed, their sessions go too), an `issued_at` timestamp, and a non‑nullable `expires_at`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. `003_add_session_index.sql` (2025-01-22)\n\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX idx_sessions_user_id ON sessions(user_id);\n```\n\n**What it does:**  \nAdds a B‑tree index on `sessions.user_id` to speed up lookups of all sessions belonging to a particular user (the most common query pattern against this table).\n\n---\n\n## 4. `004_partition_users.sql` (2025-02-18)\n\nNo file remains in the repository, but the history records it as:\n\n> **Range partition users by `created_at` (monthly).**\n\n**What it does:**  \nConverts the `users` table into a partitioned table with monthly range partitions based on `created_at`. This improves query performance, maintenance, and storage management for a table that grows steadily over time.\n\n---\n\n## 5. `005_archive_legacy_sessions.sql` (2025-03-05)\n\n> **Move >90‑day‑old sessions to `sessions_archive`.**\n\n**What it does:**  \nCreates (or populates) a `sessions_archive` table (presumably with the same schema as `sessions`) and moves sessions whose `expires_at` or `issued_at` is older than 90 days into it. This keeps the main `sessions` table lean while retaining audit‑worthy data.\n\n---\n\n## 6. `006_grant_readonly_role.sql` (2025-04-12)\n\n> **Create `app_readonly` role + grants.**\n\n**What it does:**  \nCreates a dedicated read‑only database role (`app_readonly`) and grants `SELECT` (and possibly `USAGE` on schemas) to it. This role can be used by monitoring tools, read‑only replicas, or analytics dashboards without risking writes.\n\n---\n\n## Supporting infrastructure\n\n- **`config/pg_hba.conf`** and **`config/postgresql.conf`** provide the PostgreSQL server configuration used by the migrations.\n- **`seeds/001_dev_users.sql`** inserts sample dev users after migrations have been applied.\n- **`docker-compose.yml`** orchestrates the database container.\n\n---\n\n### Summary table\n\n| # | File (or description) | Date | Purpose |\n|---|-----------------------|------|---------|\n| 001 | `001_create_users.sql` | 2024-11-04 | Base `users` table |\n| 002 | `002_create_sessions.sql` | 2024-12-10 | `sessions` table with FK to `users` |\n| 003 | `003_add_session_index.sql` | 2025-01-22 | Index on `sessions.user_id` |\n| 004 | Partition users by month | 2025-02-18 | Range partition `users` on `created_at` |\n| 005 | Archive old sessions | 2025-03-05 | Move >90‑day sessions to archive table |\n| 006 | Read‑only role | 2025-04-12 | Create `app_readonly` role and grants |\n\nIf you’re setting up a fresh environment, you’d run **001 → 002 → 003** (the files still present). For environments where the full history has already been applied, the `MIGRATION_HISTORY.md` file is the single source of truth for what has run.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 1404, "prompt_tokens": 6716, "total_tokens": 8120, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": null, "reasoning_tokens": 303, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 5632}, "prompt_cache_hit_tokens": 5632, "prompt_cache_miss_tokens": 1084}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "deepseek-v4-flash", "system_fingerprint": "fp_8b330d02d0_prod0820_fp8_kvcache_20260402", "id": "ddbcba94-4d44-4511-be24-b96e7a772ee8", "finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea3f9-243b-77d0-b197-c214351498d0-0", "tool_calls": [], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 6716, "output_tokens": 1404, "total_tokens": 8120, "input_token_details": {"cache_read": 5632}, "output_token_details": {"reasoning": 303}}}}]}}}
